]}],"annotations":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-14541/canvas/1/page/p1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-14541/canvas/1/3a990b6e-0ff7-4a7e-92cc-2f95f7f0e030","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-07-02T20:06:46.547Z","creator":"Ada ","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>As Alma dances, she is surrounded with a man in a gorilla mask and a woman in a red hat. This pair might be read as Reynolds and Alma themselves: the “most demanding” man in the world with grumpy tendencies and the energetic woman who tends to wear red and stripes. Alma’s dance in the crowd, then, is a symbolic evocation of the simultaneous tumult and joy of their relationship.&nbsp;</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-14541/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:442.9747213375796,196.98472332802547,1046.357484076433,511.9533738057325"}}}]}]}]}